cted value of a random variable, one repeatedly measures observations of the variable and computes the arithmetic mean of the results. If the expected value exists, this procedure estimates the true expected value in an unbiased manner and has the property of minimizing the sum of the squares of the residuals (the sum of the squared differences between the observations and the estimate). The law of large numbers demonstrates (under fairly mild conditions) that, as the size of the sample gets larger, the variance of this estimate gets smaller.", "qas": []}, {"context": "This property is often exploited in a wide variety of applications, including general problems of statistical estimation and machine learning, to estimate (probabilistic) quantities of interest via Monte Carlo methods, since most quantities of interest can be written in terms of expectation, e.g. formula_300, where formula_301 is the indicator function of the set formula_302.", "qas": []}, {"context": "Expected values can also be used to compute the variance, by means of the computational formula for the variance", "qas": []}, {"context": "A very important application of the expectation value is in the field of quantum mechanics. The expectation value of a quantum mechanical operator formula_304 operating on a quantum state vector formula_305 is written as formula_306. The uncertainty in formula_304 can be calculated using the formula formula_308.", "qas": []}, {"context": "The expected value of a measurable function of formula_1, formula_292, given that formula_1 has a probability density function formula_55, is given by the inner product of formula_313 and formula_314:", "qas": []}, {"context": "This formula also holds in multidimensional case, when formula_314 is a function of several random variables, and formula_313 is their joint density.", "qas": []}, {"context": "For a non-negative integer-valued random variable formula_318", "qas": []}, {"context": "If formula_320 is a non-negative random var