 already been parsed and \u03b2 is expected.", "qas": [{"question": "what is a top-down ?", "answers": [], "id": "(44, 4, 0)"}]}, {"context": "Input position 0 is the position prior to input. Input position \"n\" is the position after accepting the \"n\"th token. (Informally, input positions can be thought of as locations at token boundaries.) For every input position, the parser generates a \"state set\". Each state is a tuple (X \u2192 \u03b1 \u2022 \u03b2, \"i\"), consisting of", "qas": [{"question": "what is a tuple ?", "answers": [], "id": "(44, 5, 4)"}, {"question": "what is the position before input position ?", "answers": [], "id": "(44, 5, 0)"}]}, {"context": "\nThe state set at input position \"k\" is called S(\"k\"). The parser is seeded with S(0) consisting of only the top-level rule. The parser then repeatedly executes three operations: \"prediction\", \"scanning\", and \"completion\".", "qas": []}, {"context": "\nIt is important to note that duplicate states are not added to the state set, only new ones. These three operations are repeated until no new states can be added to the set. The set is generally implemented as a queue of states to process, with the operation to be performed depending on what kind of state it is.", "qas": []}, {"context": "The algorithm accepts if (X \u2192 \u03b3 \u2022, 0) ends up in S(\"n\"), where (X \u2192 \u03b3) is the top level-rule and \"n\" the input length, otherwise it rejects.", "qas": [{"question": "what does `` n '' mean ?", "answers": [], "id": "(44, 8, 0)"}]}, {"context": "Adapted from Speech and Language Processing by Daniel Jurafsky and James H. Martin, \nDECLARE ARRAY S;", "qas": []}, {"context": "function INIT(words)", "qas": []}, {"context": "function EARLEY-PARSE(words, grammar)", "qas": []}, {"context": "procedure PREDICTOR((A \u2192 \u03b1\u2022B\u03b2, j), k, grammar)", "qas": []}, {"context": "procedure SCANNER((A \u2192 \u03b1\u2022a\u03b2, j), k, words)", "qas": []}, {"context": "procedure COMPLETER((B \u2192 \u03b3\u2022, x), k)\nConsider the following simple grammar for arithmetic expressions:", "qas": []}, {"context": "<P> ::= <S> # the start rule\n<S> ::= <S> \"+\" <M> | <M>\n<M> ::= <M> \"*\" <T> | <T>\n<T> ::= \"1\" | \"2\" | \"3\" | \"4\"", "qas": []}, {"context": "With the input:", "qas": []}, {"context": "This is the sequence of state sets:", "qas": []}, {"context": "The state (P \u2192 S \u2022, 0) represents a completed parse. This state also appears in S(3) and S(1), which are complete sentences.", "qas": []}, {"context": "Earley's dissertation briefly describes an algorithm for constructing parse trees by adding a set of pointers from each non-terminal in an Earley item back to the items that caused it to be recognized. But Tomita noticed that this does not take into account the relations between symbols, so if we consider the grammar S \u2192 SS | b and the string bbb, it only notes that each S can match one or two b's, and thus produces spurious derivations for bb and bbbb as well as the two correct derivations for bbb.", "qas": []}, {"context": "Another method is to build the parse forest as you go, augmenting each Earley item with a pointer to a shared packed parse forest (SPPF) node labelled with a triple (s, i, j) where s is a symbol or an LR(0) item (production rule with dot), and i and j give the section of the input string derived by this node. A node's contents are either a pair of child pointers giving a single derivation, or a list of \"packed\" nodes each containing a pair of pointers and representing one derivation. SPPF nodes are unique (there is only one with a given label), but may contain more than one derivation for ambiguous parses. So even if an operation does not add an Earley item (because it already exists), it may still add a derivation to the item's parse forest.", "qas": []}, {"context": "\nNote also that SPPF nodes are never labeled with a completed LR(0) item: instead they are labelled with the symbol that is produced so that all derivations are combined under one node regardless of which alternative production they come from.", "qas": []}, {"context": "", "qas": []}, {"context": "", "qas": []}, {"context": "", "qas": []}, {"context": "", "qas": []}, {"context": "", "qas": []}, {"context": "", "qas": []}, {"context": "", "qas": []}]}, {"title": "Ethiopian cuisine", "paragraphs": [{"context": "Ethiopian cuisine () characteristically consists of vegetable and often very spicy meat dishes. This is usually in the form of \"wat,\" a thick stew, served atop \"injera\", a large sourdough flatbread, which is about in diameter and made out of fermented teff flour. Ethiopians eat most of the time with their right hands, using pieces of \"injera\" to pick up bites of entr\u00e9es and side dishes..", "qas": [{"question": "what types of food does lebanese cuisine consist of ?", "answers": [], "id": "(45, 0, 0)"}]}, {"context": "The Ethiopian Orthodox Church prescribes a number of fasting (\"tsom\", \"\u1e63\u014dm\", excluding any kind of animal products, including dairy products and eggs) periods, including Wednesdays, Fridays, and the entire Lenten season, so Ethiopian cuisine contains many dishes that are vegan.", "qas": []}, {"context": "A typical dish consists of injera accompanied by a spicy stew, which frequently includes beef, lamb, vegetables and various types of legumes, such as lentils. Gurage cuisine also makes use of the false banana plant (\"enset\", Ge'ez: \u12a5\u1295\u1230\u1275 \"inset\"), a type of ensete. The plant is pulverized and fermented to make a bread-like food called \"qocho\" or \"kocho\" (Ge'ez: \u1246\u132e \"\u1e33\u014d\u010d\u0323\u014d\"), which is eaten with kitfo. The root of this plant may be powdered and prepared as a hot drink called \"bulla\" (Ge'ez: \u1261\u120b \"b\u016bl\u0101\"), which is often given to those who are tired or ill. Another typical Gurage preparation is coffee with butter (\"kebbeh\"). \"Kita\" herb bread is also baked.", "qas": [{"q